          "body": "The chapter opens with a shut gate and an explanation that must not be read as incidental architectural regulation. The eastern gate through which the Lord's glory re-entered His temple (43:2) is to remain permanently sealed because 'the LORD God of Israel has entered by it' (44:2). Presence changes status. What the Lord has passed through cannot be treated as a common thoroughfare again. This principle — that divine entry permanently alters a threshold — runs through the whole of Ezekiel's temple vision and reaches its highest expression here. The prince is given a unique but bounded exception (v.3): he may eat bread at the gate's porch, entering and exiting by the same route, but the gate itself does not open. Even the highest human authority operates within the constraints established by the divine entry. Ezekiel's posture at the chapter's pivot (v.4 — 'I fell on my face') is the only appropriate response to seeing the glory that fills the house. The shut gate is the spatial expression of what Ezekiel does bodily: nothing approaches the Lord's presence casually."
