          "body": "The chapter's moral and structural center is the contrast between two groups of Levites who faced the same national apostasy and made opposite choices. The general Levites 'went far from Me when Israel went astray' (v.10) — they followed the nation into idolatry and specifically 'ministered to them before their idols' (v.12), becoming a stumbling block of iniquity to the house of Israel. The verdict is a permanent demotion: gate-keeping, slaughtering offerings for the people, and standing before the congregation are their assigned roles. They minister; but they minister to the people, not to the Lord. The sons of Zadok 'kept charge of My sanctuary when the sons of Israel went astray' (v.15). The same crisis, two responses. The Zadokites are given the highest priestly privilege the vision contains: 'they shall come near to Me to minister to Me... they shall enter My sanctuary... they shall come near to My table' (vv.15-16). The logic is not merely moral reward but theological fitness — those whose hearts remained oriented toward the Lord when tested are qualified to stand in the Lord's immediate presence. The Zadokite line traces historically to Zadok the priest who remained loyal to David during Absalom's rebellion (2 Samuel 15:24-29) and was confirmed by Solomon (1 Kings 2:35); Ezekiel gives this historical faithfulness an eschatological permanence."
