          "body": "Verse 23 names a priestly function that modern readers often overlook: 'they shall teach My people the difference between the holy and the profane, and cause them to discern between the unclean and the clean.' The Zadokite priest is not only a cultic functionary before the altar — he is Israel's theological educator, the one whose role is to maintain in the congregation's mind and practice the fundamental categorical distinction on which all of Mosaic religion rests. The same pairing — holy/profane, clean/unclean — appears throughout Leviticus (10:10) as the twin axes of Israel's moral and ritual world. Verse 24 adds judicial authority: in disputes, the priests stand as judges deciding according to God's ordinances, keeping His laws, statutes, feasts, and Sabbaths. The Mosaic combination of priestly and judicial function (cf. Deuteronomy 17:8-13; 21:5) is retained in Ezekiel's vision. The priest who stands before God also stands for God in the adjudication of human disputes. This dual function — upward (liturgical nearness to God) and outward (instructional/judicial service to the community) — is the fullest description of priestly vocation in the chapter, and it anticipates the New Testament's description of the church as 'a royal priesthood' (1 Peter 2:9) called to declare the excellencies of the One who called it."
